AUDIT-FIRE ORDERING RULE (2026-06-11, derived from 3 consecutive own long-gap-no-instruction deviations): in every 30-min audit fire, dispatch instruction as the FIRST spool verb IMMEDIATELY after the boot-probe (cat .status.json), BEFORE running any gmsniff/ccsniff bash scans. Reason: gmsniff/ccsniff invocations are bash (non-spool) and do NOT reset the long-gap clock, so doing them first then dispatching a spool verb after >300s gate-denies long-gap-no-instruction (happened fire #1 fetch, fire #2 was fire#1s, fire #3 memorize from the editing task). Leading with instruction resets the clock at fire-start so the post-scan spool verbs stay in-window. The pure-spool long-gap gate is by-design (iter21, core portability - no watcher-lifecycle coupling) and must NOT be changed to count bash; the fix is operational ordering. This is the new gmsniff own-deviation surfacing (v1.0.16) catching a real recurring own pattern and converting it to a preventive rule = predictability-regardless-of-LLM applied inward, working.